In [[geology]], a '''nappe''' is a large sheetlike body of [[rock (geology)|rock]] that has been moved far from its original position.  Nappes form during continental plate collisions, when folds are sheared so much that they fold back over on themselves and break apart.  The term stems from the French word for [[tablecloth]].

In [[geometry]], a '''nappe''' is one half of a double [[cone (surface)|cone]].

